name: COLOMBIA Nariño Watermelon
description:
This a one of the first experimental lots we have received from our long standing partner in Narino. With the first fermentation having fresh watermelon pieces in the tank along with the coffee, this experiment worked like a charm! From opening the bag you will smell the fresh watermelon and it will only get stronger as you brew. The initial flavor of the sip is sweet, almost candy like, moving quickly into juicy watermelon so fresh you can taste hints of the rind. With undertones of cashew and walnut this full bodied coffee is not to be missed. 
 

 

 

 It even makes a great fruity cold brew!

name: YEMEN Sana'a Manakaha
description: From Yemen's largest coffee growing region, the mountains in the Haraaz not only offer a beautiful view but also the ideal conditions for producing coffees with unique profiles. Roughly 1,500 families rely on coffee farming as their source of income. We were very happy to have found this beautiful crop of DNA verified Yemenia coffee. While not for everyone, this is truly a coffee for the coffee lovers. With notes of jasmine, white cherry, passion fruit, and a liquor-like finish.

name: BRAZIL Fazenda do Juquinha
description:
Fazenda do Juquinha is located in Maria de Fé, known for being one of the coldest cities in Minas Gerais. It is run by two brothers in law, Ivan Prado de Melo & Weder Batista, who are the only long term employees of the farm. During harvest they employ between 20-25 locals to help. 
 

 

 

 Though they are new to coffee production, their dedication to leaving and cultivating pristine practices has allowed them to produce this amazing coffee. This was a coffee we found on our trip to Brazil in 2023, and the staff has been ecstatic to have such a different and pristine profile to taste and show case at our cafe. This Yellow Catuai has a much brighter acidity than we are accustomed to finding in our Brazils and a juicy tropical stone fruit character. Still possessing the traditional cocoa and nutty profile and rich body, this Brazil is a crowd pleaser to be sure.

description: Kenya is well known for the unique flavor profile that was cultivated through the SL-28 and SL-34 varietals coupled with the volcanic terroir. Known for being full bodied and highly complex coffees, this crop from Embu County does not disappoint for anyone who loves the classic Kenyan coffee profile of black currant and tomato-like acidity.

name: ETHIOPIA Dush Lemiso Uke
description:
Since its inception in 1999, the Cup of Excellence has been an innovative, educational, and life changing program for coffee farmers. The annual competition was established both to offer farmers, particularly small holders who often lack the resources of large estates, an avenue to have their product professionally evaluated, showcased, and potentially purchased for premium retail_prices, and to incentivize a new generation of farmers to cultivate exceptional coffees. The competition is free to enter, and the top 40 coffees from each country (as chosen by a jury of experts) are auctioned with the top coffees commanding retail_prices well over 100.00 per pound.
 

 

 

 This beautiful, naturally processed Ethiopian coffee comes to us straight from the Cup of Excellence, where it received accolades for it's juicy body and complex notes of Orange Blossom, Plum, Lychee, Blueberry, Milk Chocolate, and Roasted Hazelnut. Dush Lemiso Uke is a 37 year old father of three children. He owns 0.15 hectares of land in Dawencho Kebele, Arbegona Woreda, Sidama region.

name: BURUNDI Buhorwa
description: A history of poor agricultural practices throughout Burundi's colonial history has lead to inconsistent soil quality and tree health creating drastic variances in the quality of the crop from year to year. Because of this, when an exceptional Burundi finds its way to our cupping table we are beyond thrilled. This crisp, light bodied coffee is a great way to brighten your day. With hints of lemon cake, black tea, cranberry and apricot this coffee is utterly sippable.

name: TANZANIA Hezya Peaberry
description: This beautiful peaberry coffee comes to us from the Hezya Agricultural Marketing Cooperative Society which collects from just under 300 farmers. Located in south western Tanzania between 1590-1671 MASL. This cooperative places a high priority on quality control which in turn has lead to the farmers earning a premium on their already beautiful coffees. We find this crop to be rich and smooth, with notes of raisin, toasted oats, brown sugar, and warm baking spice, making it perfect for cold weather.

name: EL SALVADOR Monte Verde
description: Grown in the Santa Ana region of El Salvador at an elevation of 1450 MASL. The producer Rene Contreras works diligently to care for his workers and community as much as he does his coffee. The dedication to quality is felt through each sip. This lovely coffee is full bodied and juicy with hints of thyme, lemon, mixed berry jam as well as cocoa and cashew to round out the deeper notes.

name: NICARAGUA Pacamara Dark Finca La Bendicion
description: Finca La Bendición sits at 1,300 MASL growing a diverse array of varietals. We at Sparrow have been particular to the Pacamaras grown here for some time now. The dedication to quality growing, harvesting, and processing is clear in the cup. With this slightly darker roast the juicy strawberry is transformed into a mixed berry jam note with a deeper body that leans into milk chocolate at the finish. If you're looking for a cozy cup with a brighter acidity, this is for you.

name: COLOMBIA Pink Bourbon
description: The crops from Colombia this year are not to be passed up. From farmers Edier Perdomo & Diego Horta we were fortunate to get a hold of this beautiful crop of Pink Bourbon. Grown in Huila in the rich volcanic soil at roughly 1800 MASL the natural characteristics of this varietal truly shine. Quickly rising through the ranks of fan favorites, this newcomer has earned the praise. With rich almond and macadamia nut sweetness coupled with apricot and stone fruit notes, this is the perfect coffee for fall.

name: NICARAGUA Pacamara Finca La Bendición
description: Finca La Bendición sits at 1,300 MASL growing a diverse array of varietals. We at Sparrow have been particular to the Pacamaras grown here for some time now. The dedication to quality growing, harvesting, and processing is clear in the cup. With floral and juicy strawberry notes pairing with a light to medium body, this coffee is sure to please.

name: ETHIOPIA Harrar Melesa
description: Natural Harrar Grade 1 is a rarity. Immature and amber cherries often find their way into naturally processed coffee from this region. Our Harrar is near zero defect. At about 1800 meters above sea level, this part of Ethiopia boasts the ideal conditions for growing indigenous heirloom varietals. Due to the lack of available water for processing, Harrar produces only natural coffees. Notes of cocoa, dried blood orange and plum, and occasional black pepper nuances offer a racy and a memorable cup each and every time.

name: BRAZIL Bourbon
description: Brazilian coffee tends to be the reference point when people talk about “coffee-flavored” anything. This particular Brazil reinforces that idea, but for discerning coffee drinkers, this Brazil stands out. It is grown slightly lower than in other coffee producing countries, inciting quicker maturation of the coffee cherry. This rapid growth smoothes out the rough edges leaving a cup that is balanced with milk chocolate notes and inherent sweetness. This coffee is 100% bourbon, firmly placing it in the classic coffee flavor category, but the hard-work and meticulous processing produces nuance and excellence that’s easily perceptible.

name: COLOMBIA Nariño Inga
description: A renowned growing region in southwestern Colombia, surrounded by high mountains and active volcanoes, Nariño offers a fascinating cup, a mixture of citric acids, fruit flavors, and an herbal aroma. This coffee is an example of the complex terroir Colombian farms have to offer. Caramel sweetness, notes of ripe grapes, a hint of raspberry, medium acidity, citrusy aftertaste, clean and pleasant cup.

name: ETHIOPIA Harrar Melesa Dark
description: When we dark roast, smoke is vacated during the roasting process for cleaner tasting notes. This leads one to find a deepening of body and richer flavors. Harrar Grade 1 coffees are a rarity. Often immature and amber cherries find their way into naturally processed coffee from this region. Our Harrar is near zero defect. At about 1800 meters above sea level, this part of Ethiopia boasts the ideal conditions for growing indigenous heirloom varietals. Due to the lack of available water for processing, Harrar produces only natural coffees. Notes of cocoa, deep rich fruits, and nuances of black pepper offer a racy and memorable cup each and every time.

name: ETHIOPIA Guji Biru Wondifraw
description: This coffee receives its unique flavor from its anaerobic processing. The coffee cherries are fermented in sealed tanks in the absence of oxygen, which means the cherries do not take on other elements from the environment. The coffee can be very sweet with lovely citrus and berry flavors. It is not very acidic or intense, but balanced and smooth.

name: ETHIOPIA Guji Wush Wush
description: Juicy tropical fruit flavors at first sip showcase the natural beauty of this coffee. This varietal is utterly unique and a pleasant refreshing surprise. You may notice the range of this coffee most as it cools to a cocoa nib profile. Our roasting has always been careful to preserve and develop terroir and this coffee benefits immensely from this philosophy. This has quickly become one of the most popular coffees at our cafe and for roastery visitors.

name: SUMATRA Arisarina Organic
description: The Arisarina Cooperative is a coffee producer cooperative established in 2013, located in the highlands of Gayo Aceh Province in Sumatra. The cooperative has a common goal to improve the quality of coffee that grows in the Gayo highlands as well as maintain and preserve the ecosystem as a place to grow the highest quality coffee beans. This region is considered one of the biggest arabica coffee regions in southeast Asia. The plantation is 100% managed by local farmers. The coffee grown in this region follows the principle of conservation, where each coffee is planted with shade trees. This kind of cultivation is rarely found in other regions in Indonesia.

name: ETHIOPIA Yirgecheffe Kochere
description: The Kochere district is located at the peak of the Yirgecheffe region, an area well known to coffee lovers for producing high quality beans. Coffee cherries in Kochere are grown in partial shade at the highest elevation in the area resulting in a dense and flavorful bean. In the cup black tea, peach, and citrus notes are paired with a refreshing, lemonade-like acidity.

name: MEXICO SIERRA MAZATECA
description: Mexico is the world’s 7th largest coffee producer, the largest exporter of organic coffees, and a fast-growing consumer of specialty coffee. The San Mateo Yoloxochitlan working group is an attempt to gather the most committed coffee growers / producers in the La Cañada region of Oaxaca. Not only are they located in one of the higher areas in the region, the coffees they produce are exceptional. This coffee is perfect for everyday, but particularly days when you need it the most. With a warmly sweet profile and silky smooth body, this has quickly become a fan favorite!

name: Espresso Havana
description: A blend of coffees from the South Pacific, this espresso is full-bodied, earthy, and a sensory overload. It is reminiscent of a classic Southern Italian espresso, but this deeply roasted selection also makes an excellent base for Cuban coffee. It is dark and bitter-sweet with a delicate acidity. The unique terroir offers notes of dried spices, green pepper, and dark chocolate.

name: Espresso Cremona
description: Using high-grade South American coffees, this roast is a perfect example of Northern European espresso accentuating rounded dry fruit with intense nuttiness. A subtle caramel sweetness lingers on the palate.

name: Espresso Marbella (ORGANIC)
description: Our flagship espresso, primarily a blend of Central and South American coffees, is an interpretation of a Spanish style espresso. Named after a coastal city in southern Spain, this espresso is light with vibrant acidity. Notes of raspberry and clementine are front and center with a smooth, milk-chocolate aftertaste.
